n","1296–Female":"1296–Overleden","1297–1377":"1297–1377","1270–1370":"1270–1370","1235–Male":"1235–Overleden","1269–Female":"1269–Overleden","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1294":"1294","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1235":"1235","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","about 1296":"circa 1296","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Tockington, Gloucestershire, England":"Tockington, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"about 1296–":"about 1296–Deceased","1294–Male":"1294–Deceased","1296–Female":"1296–Deceased","1297–1377":"1297–1377","1270–1370":"1270–1370","1235–Male":"1235–Deceased","1269–Female":"1269–Deceased","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1294":"1294","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1235":"1235","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","about 1296":"about 1296","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Tockington, Gloucestershire, England":"Tockington, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Poyntz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Points  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Points","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","from the Old French personal name <i>Ponz</i>, <i>Ponce</i>, from Latin <i>Pontius</i> (see   Ponce  ).","habitational name from any of several places called Ponts (such as those in Manche and in Seine-Maritime, Normandy), from Latin <i>pontes</i> ‘bridges’. This name has been established since the 13th century in Ireland, where it appears as <i>Pounce</i> and <i>Pounche</i>, and is Gaelicized as <b>Púinse</b>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":19,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":32,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":41,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Poyntz was born about 1296, in Tockington, Gloucestershire, England, her father, William de Poyntz, was 63 and her mother, Mrs. William de Poyntz, was 28. She had at least 1 son with Sir Henry De Frowicke Knight Of The Shire."},"et":{"about 1296–":"umbes 1296–Surnud","1294–Male":"1294–Surnud","1296–Female":"1296–Surnud","1297–1377":"1297–1377","1270–1370":"1270–1370","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1269–Female":"1269–Surnud","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1294":"1294","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1235":"1235","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","about 1296":"umbes 1296","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Tockington, Gloucestershire, England":"Tockington, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1296–":"noin 1296–Kuollut","1294–Male":"1294–Kuollut","1296–Female":"1296–Kuollut","1297–1377":"1297–1377","1270–1370":"1270–1370","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1269–Female":"1269–Kuollut","1297":"1297","1296":"1296","1294":"1294","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1269":"12